In article <9312240029591.davesparks.DLITE@delphi.com> davesparks@delphi.com (Dave Sparks) writes:

...
   would be used by enemy spies and saboteurs.  If you shut down the
   legitimate transmitters, then the clandestine ones are easier to spot.  It's
   hard to practice steganography when transmissions of any sort are prohibited.

   OTOH, when the real news of Tiananmen Square was smuggled out of China using
   FAX machines on unsecure dial-up lines, one wonders whether a modern
   "information embargo" is really possible anymore.


If you want a more recent example and one closer to home (even me, in
the UK!)  consider the attempted Canadian news embargo imposed by the
courts in a particularly ... interesting murder case this autumn.
I believe that one leaked like a sieve as well.

